biogHists.text:
Professor of communications and psychology, and director of Institute of Communications Research, University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign (earlier name: University of Illinois (Urbana-Champaign campus)).

From the description of Papers, 1939-1982. (University of Illinois at Urbana Champaign). WorldCat record id: 28409455

resource.source:
<objectXMLWrap>
               <did xmlns="urn:isbn:1-931666-22-9">
                  <unittitle>Salvador E. Luria Papers</unittitle>
                  <unitid>Mss.Ms.Coll.39</unitid>
                  <repository>
                     <corpname>American Philosophical Society</corpname>
                  </repository>
                  <langmaterial>
                     <language/>
                  </langmaterial>
                  <physdesc>
                     <extent>44.0 Linear feet</extent>
                  </physdesc>
                  <unitdate>1923-1992</unitdate>
                  <abstract>A bacteriologist from MIT, Salvador E. Luria's work with Max Delbruck on bacteriophage demonstrated that bacterial resistance to certain phages arose through genetic mutations. His later work showed that phages also mutate genetically. He received the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1969 with Max Delbruck and Alfred D. Hershey. 
                <lb/>The collection is organized into seven series: I. Correspondence, 1938-1992 ; IIa. Subject Files, 1938-1990 ; IIb. Personal Material. 1923-1991 ; III. Works by Luria, 1938-1987 ; IV. Works by Others, 1944-1990 ; V. Research Notes and Notebooks, 1941-1979 ; VI. Course Material, 1931-1991 ; VII. Photographs and Negatives, 1957-1982. Arrangement: Alphabetical by folder title and then chronological within each folder.</abstract>
                  <physloc>LH-B-42-1</physloc>
                  <origination>
                     <persname>Luria, S. E.,  (Salvador Edward), 1912-1991 </persname>
                  </origination>
               </did>
            </objectXMLWrap>
resource.title: Salvador E. Luria Papers 1923-1992
resource.abstract: A bacteriologist from MIT, Salvador E. Luria's work with Max Delbruck on bacteriophage demonstrated that bacterial resistance to certain phages arose through genetic mutations. His later work showed that phages also mutate genetically. He received the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1969 with Max Delbruck and Alfred D. Hershey. The collection is organized into seven series: I. Correspondence, 1938-1992 ; IIa. Subject Files, 1938-1990 ; IIb. Personal Material. 1923-1991 ; III. Works by Luria, 1938-1987 ; IV. Works by Others, 1944-1990 ; V. Research Notes and Notebooks, 1941-1979 ; VI. Course Material, 1931-1991 ; VII. Photographs and Negatives, 1957-1982. Arrangement: Alphabetical by folder title and then chronological within each folder.

                  </name>
                  <titleInfo>
                     <title>Papers, 1939-1982.</title>
                  </titleInfo>
                  <abstract>Correspondence; publications; mss. of writings; book reviews; clippings; course materials; subject files relating to conferences, organizations and foundations, and consulting, reviewing, and cross-cultural research in foreign countries; and other papers. Subjects include psycholinguistics, semantics, cognition, measurement of meaning, U.S. Arms Control and Disarmament Agency, Institute for Defense Analyses, nuclear policy peace research, Mankind 2000, and various concerns specific to University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, including its Institute of Communications Research and Dept. of Psychology (earlier name: University of Illinois (Urbana-Champaign campus). Dept. of Psychology), its Center for Advanced Study, and the communications doctoral program. Correspondents include William F. Brewster, Wilbur Schramm, George Suci, Percy Tannenbaum, and Christine Tanz. </abstract>
                  <name>
                     <namePart>University of Illinois at Urbana Champaign</namePart>
                     <role>
                        <roleTerm valueURI="http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/rps">Repository</roleTerm>
                     </role>
                  </name>
               </mods>
            </objectXMLWrap>
